bug.short_desc: in the resource bundle editor take into account the resources of the "Host-Plugin" when opened bundle is in a plugin-fragment

long_desc.thetext:
Hi, first thanks a lot for the message editor! It is certainly a lot of help for us already.
I have a request for improvement.
Here is the use-case: a user of eclipse-3.3.1 imports a plugin-fragment of the language-pack for eclipse-3.2.1 and needs to update it for eclipse-3.3.*
He opens one of the message.properties with the ResourceBundle editor.
The editor finds out that the project in which the resource bundle is located is a PDE project. It finds the plugin manifest and gets the targeted "Fragment-Host".
It adds to the set of properties files edited the resources that it can find inside this plugin. In this case, the plugin is not part of the workspace so the corresponding values should be read-only.
Please let me know if this makes sense.
Pascal, please evaluate.

Not only does it make sense, but support for fragments was already on my todo list. ;-) The SourceForge version had some level of support for fragments already but those are not yet ported over. Good support for fragment is definitely a must and the pattern you are describing seems like a good way to go at it. I will work at adding this.

Thanks for reviewing this Pascal.
I could not resist so I checked out your contribution in cvs... after I filed this request for improvement. From what I understood: if you load the properties from the plugin, it will try to search for fragments that target that plugin and display the related properties files.
I am not sure if you plan to support the "reverse": if you open the bundle from a properties file in a fragment: it will add to the messagebundle the resources eventually located in the targeted plugin. Even if the plugin actually belongs to the platform itself.
Thanks again!

Hi Pascal, Antoine and I worked on this bug. We hope you will consider our patch for this very useful plugin.
Both of us are eclipse-committers in the stp-bpmn project if that helps. I will attach a couple of screenshots demonstrating what we did and then a patch against the current source commmitted in cvs.
Thanks for your attention.

This improvement to the editor will help updating existing i18n fragments.

Also this patch support loading the root-locale from the host-plugin when that plugin is located in the workspace. (TODO: attach screenshot).

When the host-plugin is developed in the same workspace and contains the root resource inside as source folder, the editor can load it too and it is editable.

when the host-plugin is a project in the same workspace and the root resource is located inside a library of that plugin the editor can also load it. It will be read-only though.

First, thank you for your patch. I have committed the code with some minor changes. But I could not test that everything is working properly. Please review the following:
[MessagesBundle] The rendering of a locale being a UI concern, I did not commit the code where you have the word "Default" hard-coded. I prefer to leave it to the Editor to decide how to name locales.
[NLFragmentBundleGroupStrategy] StringBuilder not present in 1.4 (supported plugin JDK version). I changed it to StringBuffer.
[EntryLeftBanner] The string "(read-only)" was not internationalized.
[I18Entry] isEditable makes reference to TextEditor. Long-term plans for the I18NPage is to be used with other sources (not just TextEditor). Making it dependent on TextEditor makes it much less reusable. Ways to take it out will have to be found.
[UIUtils] fixed a null pointer when locale is null in your sorting comparasion.
I changed the message key: editor.i18nentry.rootlocale.label from "Root" to "Default" to use consistent naming with elsewhere in the plugin.
But more importantly (and the reason for re-assigning this ticket back to you), I could not get your NL fragment solution to work with the messages.properties files contained within the nls fragment of the Babel editor plugin. Have you successfully done so?

Thanks a lot Pascal for taking the patch and fixing it... so quickly! Let me know if you want me to mark this as fixed.
If you want me to work on related scenarios and keep this bug opened please let me know. For example: at this point I would feel at ease adding support to what you suggested: open a resource bundle in the host-plugin and the localized resources in the fragments that target that plugin.
Antoine or myself will certainly join the next dev-conf call. We are very interested in the builders to help a user see the state of completion of a translation project.

Sorry I did not answer your question:
No Antoine and have not worked on the particular scenario where the localized properties are inside an nl folder in the fragment.
We will work on it tomorrow.
Just to make sure; the scenarios to support are: 1- Opening /org.eclipse.babel.editor.nls/messages.properties should locate the french locale /org.eclipse.babel.editor.nls/nl/fr/messages.properties
2- Opening /org.eclipse.babel.editor.nls/nl/fr/messages.properties should locate the root locale /org.eclipse.babel.editor.nls/messages.properties
3- Assuming the root messages.properties was actually inside the host-plugin: /org.eclipse.babel.editor/messages.properties, opening /org.eclipse.babel.editor.nls/nl/fr/messages.properties should load it.

I think the scenario you are describing would cover a broad range of options and I am all for it so feel free to go ahead.
Your interest in the builders makes me happy. I wanted that for a while. I have something that I feel works fine already, but my question is how do we go about associating a "translation" nature to a project. Do we automatically do it for all Java projects or we leave it to a user with a feature like "Add Translation Capabilities...".
I unfortunately do not thing I will be able to make it to the next conf call (but I usually do not miss any).

So for adding support to the nl folder, we are first waiting to confirm it is a good idea as asked on the mailing list: http://dev.eclipse.org/mhonarc/lists/babel-dev/msg00100.html
Otherwise, you made me realize I had not test the builder. It turns out the new code breaks the build. So I am working on that obviously and will send another patch.
Regarding strategies to setup the builder in the project description we can discuss various options that we have been through when developing the validation builder of stp-bpmn although listening to project's creation and updates will certainly work.
In stp-bpmn we add the validation builder when a new diagram is created.

Is this just an editor or does this actually help you create the NL-projects from say a normal plug-in?

this editor does not generate the NLS subclass, it does not touch Java code. You still get to create the fragment by hand, and create at least one localized property file.
This tool is more for translators.
Have a look at the screenshots Hugues made, this one should help get a good idea of the editor: https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/attachment.cgi?id=86630
fantastic... we have work going on in PDE to help create the various NL projects (bug 201998) so I'm curious to see where the intersection will be.

I think you guys finish where the editor starts, ie you create the files, the editor helps filling them up.
However it sounds like we all need to agree on how we organize those files. I have started a thread on babel-dev to ask for precisions regarding pieces of the process that need to be made very clear: http://dev.eclipse.org/mhonarc/lists/babel-dev/msg00100.html

To correct what has been said above, I have recently committed a new wizard that will actually create the resource bundles from scratch. At this moment, it only supports the "traditional" way of creating resource bundles (all properties files in the same folder/package). Nothing prevents adapting it to let the user pick the type of NL "packaging" he prefers (giving the option as radio button in the same wizard, or creating different wizards for each type).
To try it, go to New.../Other.../Messages Editor/ResourceBundle

(In reply to comment #23)
How similar is this to the work going on in PDE with bug 201998?

Created attachment 86899 screeshot of the "New Resource Bundle" wizard.
(In reply to comment #24) Chris,
This wizard is very different from the one developed in bug 201998.
The wizard creates a single resource bundle unrelated to NLS and eclipse-plugin developments. It could be used for a standard java project or any project that relies on resource bundles.
I hope this helps.
Oh cool, a picture really is worth a thousand words :)

Cheers!
Well it is really good to know that you guys are working on that wizard: we will make sure to not file a request for improvement to duplicate that work ;-)
As far as my company is concerned we are proposing improvements that target the translator. Our translators will not be professionals with their own set of translation tools. They won't be java developers either. They will be users of our product who are familiar with the eclipse-platform.
We have been using the PDE toolset to refactor our code for i18n and we were fine with it... although we probably wished we had the wizard described in bug 201998: nice one!

Created attachment 87929 patch with code for improvement to the builder setup
This patch focuses on the changes to provide the enhancement suggested by Pascal for the setup of the rbe builder:
- new preference to be able to add the nature and builder automatically. - when the plugin is started, if the preference is true, goes through the projects with javanature and setup the nature if it is not there. - when the preference is switched to true, same as above. - when the preference is set to false a popup to offer to disable the already setup builders. - divided the toggle nature action into 2 actions that are aware whether the nature is going to be added or removed: only a single menu item appears and it displays the result of the action in advance instead of the ambiguous "Add/Remove" thing. - when the preference is true and the message editor opens a file inside a java project, it will also configure the rbe nature if it could not be found.

Created attachment 87936 screenshot of the preferences for the reports page
The screenshot shows the suggested change in the report where each type of validation is setup a level of reporting, similar to the Error/Warning prefernce page of the Java compiler in JDT.
When the level is "ignore" the validation builder will not generate the error at all.
In this screenshot is also showed a small improvement in the GotoMarker of the editor: it will now try to open the master page and select the related key. This as suggested in some commented code of the editor.
I suggest a new preference related to the report of duplicate values in a given properties file. I think this kind of thing can only be changed inside the default properties file: if the default properties file has many keys with the same values, the other localized file are most likely to be in the same situation.

Created attachment 87937 full patch with all changes since the last commit of Pascal
This patch holds all the changes for the suggested improvement since the last commit of Pascal.
It contains: - support for a filter of the locales the user is working on. - transparent setup of the rbe nature and builder. - ability to customize a little more the reports generated by the builder - refactoring of the builder to minimize the creation of MessageResourceBundleGroup during each build.
I don't have other improvements in mind at this point for the editor and the i18n validator. Don't hesitate to come and chat for reveiw when you have time.
Hopefully the editor will be in use sometimes next week by amateur translators for my work.
PLease re-open if I missed something.

My apologies for that. Looks like the UI must be confusing now....
So do we still want to support the "nl structure" for properties files? It sounds like this is not a best practice: http://dev.eclipse.org/mhonarc/lists/babel-dev/msg00108.html

Regarding support for the "nl" structure. It is in fact very hard to support.
For example let's edit the file: /myproject/nl/fr/CA/foo/messages.properties
it is not possible to know whether foo is a variant or a sub-folder. We can try to search for: /myproject/foo/ if it does not exist we can assume that foo is a variant.
Now things get pretty ambiguous very quickly. Take this clumsy structure: /myproject/ messages.properties foo/messages.properties nl/fr/CA/ messages.properties foo/messages.properties
Now foo can very well be a variant or a sub-folder. So the algorithm makes the arbitrary decision to make the existence of /myproject/foo/ prevale so foo is not considered a variant.
Things get a lot more complicated when loading things from a fragment as there are multiple places where to search for the existence of that folder.
I am almost done supporting this when editing and validating files from a fragment.
I am still surprise that this nl-folder structure is a best practice when dealing with properties files.

Created attachment 88843 add support for loading files locted in fragments from the host plugin
When the file opened is in the host-plugin: - nl folder is looked up if the file opened does not have a locale suffix and is not inside a source folder. - fragments that target the host plugin are looked up (except during the build as the build validates one project at a time). Fragments are only searched inside the workspace. Editable files only are searched: not derived files, not resources located inside jars. Fragments located in the platform are not searched either.
The limitations above make sense in my opinion for proper usage of the tool: if the user edits a host plugin we assume he only expects the resources of the fragment that he is also developing in the same workspace to be looked up.
Also there was a trivial bug to fix that was preventing the resources found in the jars to be loaded: please make sure that the check is made on line 209 of NLFragmentBundleGroupStrategy.

Ok. I tested briefly all the cases mentioned here and I believe this request for improvement is fulfilled. If this is useful to you I can export the workspace I used for testing those, cleaned of non-EPL files of course.

The missing check line 209 NLFragmentBundleGroupStrategy was my mistake. Sorry about that.
Let me know how it works for you.

I have checked your patch in. One thing is still missing to close this ticket. You have it working both ways for "NL" files (from host to fragments and from fragments to host). That is awesome.
What is missing is the same feature for "traditional" properties files spread accross plugin/fragments (NOT using the NL structure). This is a plausible scenario for files like the plugin.properties which have to be in the root of plugin/fragments (so it was explained to me). Using NL structure for the plugin.properties does not work when referenced in config files and what not. (Look for the plugin.properties in the Babel editor project for an example).
It should also be supported for people using traditional properties files across plugins/fragments for other purposes as well.
The scenario you describe is working for me. Please provide a test case.

Created attachment 88966 patch to support the proper behavior even if the platofrm is not PDE.
After chatting with Pascal we managed to reproduce the issue. It happens when the algos are calling IProject#getNature(natureId) but the plugin that defines the corresponding nature is not available.
In that case an exception is thrown and nothing happens.
The fix consist of coding our own .project parser to return the expected answer even if the nature-object (PDE or java-project) is not available.

The last patch supports the environment in which Pascal was testing. ... Well hopefully !
Please re-open with a test case if it does not work for you.

I could now test successfully with your latest fix. That is, by launching a new workspace and importing the babel plugin project for testing.
When installing the plugin and testing on my actual Eclipse install, I still have the last problem described. Since it now works whenever I launch a new workspace, I am thinking this last problem might be related with my current Eclipse install and I am going to close this. Thank you very much for that very handy contribution.
Thanks for the review and testing. Nice collaborating with you.
